- checkpoint_step=0 is falsy in Python: `m.get("checkpoint_step") or m.get("checkpoint_id")` in eval_domino/skills/benchmark_skills.py passed `--checkpoint_id None` for zeroshot/base models (step 0) → server dies with FileNotFoundError '.../None/assets/'. Fixed on disk with an `is not None` check (benchmark_skills.py:99). Data-level workaround that works even on a stale live driver: add `"checkpoint_id": 0` to the model section of runs/<id>/config.json.
- runs/<id>/config.json is re-read at every run_pending_shards window and every shard launch; eval_domino code is imported ONCE at driver start. Under a live driver: data fixes (config.json) act immediately, code fixes only after a driver restart. Choose the fix surface accordingly.
- Port 9100 is the system node_exporter (foreign process listening on *:9100 — NEVER kill it). The old `port = 9100 + gpu_id` in eval_domino/benchmarks/domino.py made every GPU-0 shard die at bind with EADDRINUSE — masked until the model loads far enough to reach bind(), since import/load crashes happen first. Port base moved to 9210 on disk; until a driver restart picks that up, exclude GPU 0 via resources.gpu_ids in the run's config.json (GPU 0 hardware itself is fine — restore it after restart).
- policy_model_server.py imports envs → open3d → needs libGL.so.1, which on this box exists ONLY in /work/markhsp/miniforge3/envs/domino/lib. shard_cmd's server line now exports LD_LIBRARY_PATH explicitly (domino.py) instead of relying on the parent shell. The pi05 smoke test does NOT import envs/open3d, so SMOKE_OK does not cover the server's sim-dependency import path.
- "Stream closed" on every mcp__skills__ call = the SDK driver process died (confirm: walk ppid from your Bash shell; the claude pid is reparented to 1). The harness respawns a fresh driver + benchmark_agent that takes over the node. The orphaned session must NOT drive the queue (no retry/skip/complete_node — a stray complete could clobber the live successor). Channels that still work: append an OPERATOR NOTE to the failing shard's .log (the successor reads it via log_tail/shard_log_tail), data-level config.json fixes, and this memory file.
- Shard .log files append across attempts (multiple SERVER_FAILED_TO_START blocks per file); the LAST traceback is the current failure. `attempts` in task_plan.json counts launches, not fix attempts.
- Crashed shard runners can LEAK policy_model_server.py children (ppid=1, ~57GB GPU memory each, listening on dead old-scheme ports). nvidia-smi showing memory on a "free" GPU with util 0% = check for orphans. Safe-reap recipe: match /proc/PID/cmdline against the run's model_name/checkpoint before killing (avoids PID reuse and foreign processes); SIGTERM reaped them cleanly. The *:9100 listener is always node_exporter — verify via ss that the orphan's fd is NOT the 9100 binding before assuming. Found 4 such orphans (GPUs 0-3) from the pre-fix 04:56 attempt of eval_ab_zeroshot on 2026-06-11.
- DOMINO client/server import split: eval_policy_client.py (domino conda env, py3.10, NO jax) imports the policy module ('pi05') for encode_obs/eval/reset_model — but module-level `from pi_model import *` + `import dill` in policy/pi05/deploy_policy.py pulled jax/dill into the client env → ModuleNotFoundError for every shard (both A/B runs). Fix 2026-06-11: lazy-import `from pi_model import PI0` inside get_model() (server-only path; star-import is illegal inside a function), removed stray module-level dill/torch; also pip-installed dill==0.3.8 into the domino env (additive, zero deps) before realizing the lazy import made it unnecessary. Client only ever uses ModelClient(port) — get_model at client line 222 is resolved-but-never-called legacy. Preflight both envs after touching deploy_policy.py: domino python imports pi05; pi05 .venv python imports pi_model (use CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES='' JAX_PLATFORMS=cpu to keep GPUs untouched).
- Orchestrator auto-fails a shard at 3 launches ('program_error; attempts exhausted') WITHOUT offering fix mode — and retry_shard'ing N shards at once before the next (unknown) systemic error is diagnosed can burn the last launch of all N at once (lost 4 early-task shards to the dill error this way). Discipline: after any systemic fix, preflight outside the queue (direct python import/run), then retry the minimum set; revive the rest after one clean window. retry_shard works on status=failed too, so attempts-exhausted shards are recoverable once the real fix is in.
- DOMINO client/server retrofit was HALF-BUILT (first end-to-end shakeout 2026-06-11): server dispatched cmds as model methods with 0-or-1 arg only, client sent module-level func names ('reset_model') and deploy_policy.eval() touched PI0 attrs (observation_window, pi0_step) on ModelClient. Fixed: (1) policy_model_server.py protocol now takes "args" list → method(*args), legacy "obs" kept; (2) ModelClient duck-types the PI0 surface eval() uses — reset_model→reset_obsrvationwindows RPC, set_language, update_observation_window(args=[img_arr,state]), get_action→np.asarray, local observation_window mirror (None on reset / truthy on update — eval only checks `is None`), pi0_step injected from usr_args (deploy_policy.yml pi0_step: 50); (3) ModelClient.call raises RuntimeError with server traceback when response has "error" — the old code died with opaque KeyError:'res'. Cheap preflight that needs NO model load: run real ModelServer with a stub PI0 (pi05 venv) + real ModelClient (domino env) over localhost — /tmp/stub_model_server.py + /tmp/client_integration_test.py pattern. DOMINO script files are read fresh per shard launch (new processes), so these fixes need no driver restart.
- run_pending_shards max_minutes is declared as type string in the MCP schema but the implementation does float+max_minutes arithmetic → passing it at all yields {"error": "TypeError: unsupported operand type(s) for +: 'float' and 'str'"} and the window does NOT run. Always call run_pending_shards with run_id only.
- HARNESS RESPAWN REGENERATES THE SIBLING'S config.json FROM THE LAUNCH TEMPLATE (observed 2026-06-11 12:27:47 on eval_ab_robotwin30k; eval_ab_zeroshot's survived untouched — regeneration is not consistent, always CHECK mtime + contents after any respawn). Regeneration reset gpu_ids [4,5,6,7]→[0,1,2,3], colliding with eval_ab_zeroshot on BOTH GPUs and ports (port = 9210+gpu_id): the surviving server of each port pair would have served the WRONG checkpoint to the other run's client → silently poisoned A/B metrics, recorded as 'done'. Cross-run port collision is invisible to each agent alone — each just sees its own EADDRINUSE. Established split: eval_ab_zeroshot=GPUs 0-3 (ports 9210-9213), eval_ab_robotwin30k=GPUs 4-7 (ports 9214-9217). Resolution from an orphaned session (MCP dead): restore sibling config.json gpu_ids (re-read every window), SIGTERM the colliding shard runners DURING MODEL LOAD (pre-bind = the only safe window; their EXIT traps reap the servers), operator notes in the killed shards' logs telling the sibling agent to just retry_shard.
- 'Tool permission stream closed before response received' on an mcp__skills__ call = same dead-driver family as 'Stream closed', but check WHICH process died: this time the claude driver survived (reparented to pid 1) and the PARENT harness (eval_domino.cli) was what died — the sdk-type MCP server lives in the harness, so skills die while Bash/Read/Edit keep working. Harness respawn brings a new driver + agent session that owns the queue; the old session must stand down from queue ops but retains full file/process channels.
- Harness respawn does NOT preserve run progress: on the 2026-06-11 12:27 respawn, eval_ab_zeroshot's task_plan.json was reset (7 done -> pending, attempts zeroed) and shards/*.log were truncated; it relaunched from the first tasks. The ground truth that DOES survive is DOMINO/eval_result/<task>/pi05/<task_config>/<model>/*/_metrics.json (parse_shard_result reads newest per task) — so a reset costs re-run compute, not data. Do NOT edit task_plan.json under a live harness (it holds the plan in memory and rewrites the file each window; config.json is the only safe data-fix surface). Also: someone hardened ModelServer.start() post-respawn to os._exit(2) on bind failure (a server that cannot bind must die, not linger holding ~57GB) — keep that.
- shard_log_tail has the same string-typed-param bug as run_pending_shards: passing max_bytes returns {"error": "TypeError: bad operand type for unary -: 'str'"} and no log. Call it with run_id+shard_id only. Also, run_pending_shards' program_error response can carry an EMPTY log_tail field — always fall back to shard_log_tail before concluding anything.
- Orphan-session sequencing (2026-06-11 12:32, robotwin30k node): when mcp__skills__ calls return "Stream closed", the harness successor may ALREADY be live and past the failure before you finish diagnosing — BEFORE writing operator notes or applying data fixes, check `ps -eo pid,ppid,etime,cmd | grep 'eval_domino.cli run <run_id>'` for a fresh driver and re-read task_plan.json (my 4 error_paused shards were already status=running on GPUs 4-7 under the successor). Tool calls that returned "Stream closed" did NOT land (my 4 retry_shard calls had no effect; the successor issued its own) — never assume partial effect. Stale operator notes written after the successor has moved on are noise: verify first, write second.
